Karana Server</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubatou062671.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Batou062671</A> at: 12/13/01 10:28:15 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umarkneill.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MarkNeill</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(12/14/01 7:22:48 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Patch December 13th, 12:00am</span><hr size=1> The s3d files on your hard drive hold the compressed textures and zone layout for every zone in EQ.<br>
<br>
Each time you zone, the required file in unpacked into memory.  The zone is layed out, the textures are rebuilt from the compressed structures, then applied to the zone.<br>
<br>
The new TextureCache will look for the textures on disk.  If they aren't on disk, instead of unpacking them into RAM, it will unpack them onto disk.  It will then load them into RAM from disk.  Batou has the right idea.<br>
<br>
Pointers won't help make the cache smaller.  And they'll cause another layer of memory redirection, having to look up more addresses.  So it's only 1 operation, not a big deal?  No, but multiply that by the number of times you encounter a texture in a zone, and you start running into multiple clock cycles each time a new object comes into your clip plane.<br>
<br>
They state it won't help with 512+ of RAM - you've already got enough RAM space that the system doesn't need to swap to free space to do the unpacking and rendering of the textures.  And it won't help the first time you zone, but it should help later zones.<br>
<br>
And 1.5G is a worst-case scenario.  Besides, these aren't highly-compressed JPG images they're using for textures, they're more akin to raw image files.  Ever scanned a picture in Photoshop, and looked at the file properties of the RAW file before you convert to JPG?  That 35K JPG took about 2M when in RAW format.<br>
<br>
Images in usable format are huge.  Expecting to store them in non-compressed format and not take as much as a gig and a half is, well, overestimating the ability of your computer :) <p><BR>
